@Amierah Comet —-

How does the age of a country’s population affect it?

The age of the U.S. population is getting older. Do you see an affect?

@Jayden 
Hi Jayden! I like that you supported your observations with evidence from the graph, such as the size of the circles indicating the size of the population of individual countries. 
Like China, I notice that Europe is also aging as well. Do you think all countries are trending towards an older population?

@Sergey 
Hi Sergey!
A population can certainly age by having fewer births. What other factors do you think might make a population age?

@Brooke Z 
Hi Brooke! You ask a good question: Why the population shifts so much over time when people are dying and being born.  It seems that the overall age of each country would remain the same if the number of births equal the number of deaths. 

These graphs tell a different story, as you have seen. What might be causing the change in population age?

@Salma Luna 
Hi Salma! I love how you explained the purpose of the three maps and that you have concluded that the population is transitioning from working-age to older. I also like that you cited how the populations of specific countries have changed over time. 

Do you think it is possible that older populations may ever revert back to being a younger population?

@Deniciya Butler 
Hi Deniciya! I agree that the world largely consisted of younger populations in 1990.  What aspect of the graph led you to notice this? 

It also certainly is surprising that there were no countries with older populations in 1990. What might have prevented countries from having a surplus of older individuals?

@Noah 
Hi Noah! Thanks for your thoughts. I also see that Nigeria's population has remained young because it has remained dark blue from 1990 to 2023 and is expected to stay that way in 2050. 

How do you think a population stays "mostly young"?  What might be different about Africa that is causing the population to remain young?

@Matt Ferreira 
Hi Matt! It certainly is interesting that Japan is the only country to have an older population in 2023. What do you think has allowed Japan to have an older population while all other countries of the world have not made it to that point yet?

I also love your headline! Look for it in the Reveal!
